    "topic": "How to manage and dealing with fake content on social media.",
    "opinion": "As someone who's lived through many changes in how we communicate, I've seen firsthand how social media can be both a blessing and a curse. At my age, with my background growing up with parents who had no formal education, I learned early to question what I hear and see. That's become even more important now with all the fake content floating around online. I only check social media a few times monthly, mostly to see pictures of my grandchildren and keep up with my church group, but even in that limited exposure, I've encountered misleading posts. My approach to managing fake content comes from my Christian values and life experience. First, I always pause before sharing anything. My high agreeableness score means I want to help others, but I've learned that sharing false information, even with good intentions, can harm people. I think about whether something aligns with what I know to be true from my own life or from trusted sources like my pastor or local community leaders. Second, I rely on my moderate conscientiousness to fact-check when something seems off. Just last month, I saw a post about a supposed local emergency that turned out to be completely fabricated. Instead of panicking, I called a neighbor who works at the city office to verify. Third, I use my creative side to think critically about why someone might create fake content. Often it's to stir up emotions or push an agenda. My low openness score means I'm cautious about new ideas that contradict my established beliefs, but I balance that with my Christian teaching to seek truth. Finally, I focus on building real connections. My hobbies like volunteering and hiking keep me grounded in my Kansas City community where I can have face-to-face conversations. When I do encounter fake content, I sometimes gently correct it if I know the person, or I simply disengage. Social media companies should do more, but ultimately, each of us has responsibility. My advice to others, especially younger people who spend more time online, is to develop the same skepticism my parents taught me through their hard-earned wisdom, even without formal schooling.",
